n","1325–Female":"1325–Overleden","1327–Male":"1327–Overleden","1339–Male":"1339–Overleden","1340–Female":"1340–Overleden","1365–Female":"1365–Overleden","1293–1355":"1293–1355","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","1355":"1355","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","about 1365":"circa 1365","1293":"1293","ABT 1339":"circa 1339","1339":"1339","Of,, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1339–":"about 1339–Deceased","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1327–Male":"1327–Deceased","1339–Male":"1339–Deceased","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1293–1355":"1293–1355","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","1355":"1355","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","about 1365":"about 1365","1293":"1293","ABT 1339":"about 1339","1339":"1339","Of,, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clement","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Alcide, Alphonse, Andre, Marcel, Armand, Cecile, Christophe, Gaston, Olivier, Aime.","English, Catalan, German, Flemish, and Dutch; French and Walloon (<b>Clément</b>): from the Latin personal name <i>Clemens</i> meaning ‘merciful’ (genitive <i>Clementis</i>). This achieved popularity firstly through having been borne by an early Christian saint who was a disciple of Saint Paul, and later because it was selected as a symbolic name by a number of early popes. There has also been some confusion with the personal name <i>Clemence</i> (from Latin <i>Clementia</i>, meaning ‘mercy’, an abstract noun derived from the adjective; in part a masculine name from Latin <i>Clementius</i>, a later derivative of <i>Clemens</i>). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, especially Italian   Clemente  , and also their derivatives."],"variants":[{"name":"Clem","meanings":["English (Somerset): from a short form of the personal name   Clement   or of the female form, <i>Clemence</i>.","Americanized form of German <b>Klemm</b> and German or Dutch <b>Klem</b>: from a short form of the personal name   Klemens  ."]},{"name":"Clements","meanings":["English, Irish (Tyrone and Antrim), and Dutch: variant of   Clement  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Clementz   and Slovenian patronymic <b>Klemenc</b> (see   Klements  )."]},{"name":"Clemente","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Elia, Manuel, Cesar, Fernando, Luis, Rafael, Alfredo, Andres, Armando, Gerardo.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Salvatore, Vito, Gino, Angelo, Nicola, Rocco, Enrico, Guido, Marco, Matteo.  Portuguese Joaquim.","Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese: from the personal name<i>Clemente</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Crimi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Gaetano, Vita, Cosimo, Giuseppe, Luciano, Luigi, Sal, Tommaso.","Italian (Sicily): from an altered form of the medieval Greek personal name <i>Klēmēs</i>, from Latin <i>Clemens</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Chimenti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Francesco, Filomena, Guido.","Italian (southern): variant of <b>Clementi</b> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clemon","meanings":["English: probably from a variant of the personal name   Clement  .","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish and northern Irish   McClymont  ."]},{"name":"Klehm","meanings":["North German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Klement</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clementson","meanings":["English: from the personal name   Clement   + <i>-son</i>. See also   Clements   and   Clemson  .","Americanized form of Swedish <b>Klementsson</b> or <b>Clementsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Klement</i>,   Clement  .","Americanized form of Danish and Norwegian <b>Clementsen</b> or <b>Klementsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."]},{"name":"Kelemen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Andras, Gabor, Geza, Imre, Laszlo, Tibor, Bela, Gyula, Istvan, Jozsef, Karoly, Leszlo.","Hungarian, Croatian, Slovak, Rusyn, and Slovenian: from the personal name <i>Kelemen</i>, Hungarian form of   Clement  . The Hungarian surname is also common in Romania."]},{"name":"Climie","meanings":["Scottish: from a Scots pet form of the personal name   Clement  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Clement was born about 1339, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Robert Clement. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Delaber."},"et":{"ABT 1339–":"umbes 1339–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1327–Male":"1327–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1293–1355":"1293–1355","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","1355":"1355","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","about 1365":"umbes 1365","1293":"1293","ABT 1339":"umbes 1339","1339":"1339","Of,, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Carmarthenshire, Wal